@article{Chase2019,
abstract = {Although evidence suggests that humans have elevated global extinction rates and lowered global species richness, species richness at scales smaller than the globe can increase, decrease or remain the same. However, the role of spatial scale is rarely considered as a modifier in driving how richness change unfolds. We first observed richness change over nested spatial scales in a simulation model after environmental change that altered rates of colonizations and extinctions. While being dependent on assumptions (e.g. non‐equilibrium versus equilibrium), we generally find that richness change depends on spatial scale (including larger, smaller or hump‐shaped changes in species richness with increasing scale). Using four case studies, we show different forms of scale‐dependent richness change through time. Some show increasing magnitudes of richness change with scale, while others show decreasing magnitudes of richness change with scale; some even show reversals, where richness change switches from negative to positive, or vice versa, across scales. Finally, we collated data from a heterogeneous set of studies of different taxa from small plots to the globe. We found variable results, which although confounded in ways that preclude strong inference, nevertheless suggest scale‐dependence in several taxa. In all, we show that an observation of an increase or decrease, or no change at all, in richness change through time at a single scale cannot be used to infer change at other scales. Instead, understanding how biodiversity is changing in the Anthropocene requires estimates that explicitly incorporate scale‐dependence. This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.},
