abstract = {Incorporating biological effects of environmental variability into predictions of species' performance is a persistent challenge that limits our ability to project across temporal scales in ecology. Here we test the hypothesis that population growth rates in fluctuating thermal environments can be predicted quantitatively from the curvature of thermal performance curves (TPCs) using scale transition theory. Using experimental populations of the green alga Tetraselmis tetrahele grown over a range of temperatures in constant and fluctuating thermal regimes, we show that population growth rates in fluctuating thermal regimes can be accurately and quantitatively predicted based on performance in constant thermal regimes. We extrapolate from these results to predict how population growth and critical temperatures for persistence of 89 phytoplankton species assessed in constant conditions would differ in naturally variable thermal environments. Together these results demonstrate a key improvement upon our ability to predict population dynamics in the context of global change.},
